node.text: Two cubes, this means the audio samples are being brought up to the 9th power. To make sure the wave doesn't exponentially decrease we set the gain all the way up to 1.0 (1 to any power is still 1). We'll lower it later.

On the top is a spikey sine wave with only the top portions. On the bottom is the bottom of a triangle wave (which lets be real, is pretty much a spikey sine wave).
Then we stitch them together so the top and bottom parts of the waves come from different wave primitves.
Move the volume back down - we couldn't before because of those two cubes.
Not a useful instrument, but seems to have a lot of potential for creating campy machine and robotics foley. 56K modem?
Using a supersaw as a Lerp factor - it's somewhere between a low tone and LFO.
Lerp between most a Sine and a shifted version of itself.
Low tone/LFO to give it that plucky wobble.

An example of how to start building up to a supersaw.
The basic premise is to combine a bunch of similar sawtooths together, which is done with a chorus as a VERY low offset which adds a phasey effect.
The key to this instrument is here. Notice how to chorus offset is HUGE. This creates dissonance from the tone being played.
LFO switching between the Triangle series.
This is probably expensive. A bunch of Decays with different note frequency settings.
We gotta really lower the signal from it being boosted super high from all those Delay nodes.
Take the wobbling upper partials and the root signal, and LFO it with just the root.
Buffer and repeat the raising sound. Not 100% sure, but recording the signal and playing it through a cycle is probably cheaper than keeping it streaming with a Sawtooth LFO.
A simple example of combining multiple sines to fill in upper partials.
"Hey,... want to hear the most annoying sound in the world?"
A sawtooth with a simple upper partial at x2 the frequency and one at x3 freq with its own dedicated chorus settings.
Blend the cyling audio a bit.
The toggling from playing to not playing gives it its signature gurgling effect.
Clips the ends of the waveform's shape to give the sine waves slightly more of a square wave quality.
A small series of delays with different settings.
A stairstepping of adding sines to fill in upper partials for a root sine tone.
The root sine followed by upper partials. Notice how the upper partials are just incrementing integers with the timing set to a multiple of the note frequency.

These upper partials also have envelopes to make sure they fade away pretty quickly.
It's a common strategy for emulating "hammer" instruments, such as pianos and xylophones. Multiple upper partials that fade away quickly.

Nothing fancy.
An example of just a sine wave, but with an all-in-one ASDR connected to it.
Curve a triangle by raising it to a power, then stair step it, and then delay the macrel out of it.
This instrument gets its initial hard "early-slap" from a dection of it decaying earlier than the rest.
LFO to transition between vibratoed and overdriven.
Clamp the signal to give it more of a square quality. When we switch back and forth in the LFO, it will sound like we're transitioning to an overdrive.

Doing something exerimental here, one is tied to the BPM and one is tied to the note frequency.
Notes that harmonize with the BPS may directly add or phase cancel.
Mainly clamping for distortion. Keep in mind changing the PowerAmp will also change what we clamp and distort.

Some amplitude modulated white noise backtracking a sine wave. Kind of feels like the sound is slowly being toasted.
The master and volume may need to be raised to notice the noise.
White noise gated at high frequencies, with a bit of added processing.
Body. We don't have to be too careful about having this in the correct range because we're going to PowerAmp and clamp afterwards.
A harsher sawtooth. Notice that since the nodegraph behind the section is so complex, a delay is preffered over a chorus.
And it's backtracked by a softer saw for a little extra fill.
The sound gets its timbre from lerping constantly between two different tones - which themselves are made of primitive waves which combined us 4 unique types.
